## Analysis

### Slow Sections Identification
The primary computation-heavy section is the matrix multiplication loop:

```systemverilog
// Multiply (SLOW in SV!)
for (i = 0; i < N; i++)
    for (j = 0; j < N; j++)
        for (k = 0; k < N; k++)
            C[i*N+j] = C[i*N+j] + A[i*N+k] * B[k*N+j];
```

This is a standard $O(N^3)$ matrix multiplication. While SystemVerilog is designed for hardware description, complex, floating-point intensive arithmetic operations involving deep loops (especially those that mimic high-level language computation rather than parallel hardware structures) can significantly slow down the simulation time, particularly when using floating-point types (`real`).

### Why DPI-C Helps
Direct Programming Interface (DPI-C) allows us to offload these intensive, sequential, floating-point calculations to highly optimized C code. C compilers are extremely efficient at handling complex arithmetic and memory operations, making the simulation time much faster compared to executing the same logic within the SystemVerilog simulator kernel.

We will encapsulate the entire matrix multiplication logic into a single C function call.

